<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=UTF-8"></head><body ><div>Compile with -traceback and -check all if using Intel. &nbsp; Otherwise find the right compiler options to check array bounds accesses and to dump a stack trace. Then compile debug and run that way. Assuming it fails, you probably will get good info on the source of the problem. If it doesn't fail then the compiler has a bug (not as rare as you might think).</div><div><br></div><div>You need to look at the application output. Not the output from mpirun.</div><div><br></div><div>Ed</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><div style="font-size:75%;color:#575757">Sent via the Samsung Galaxy Sâ„¢ III, an AT&amp;T 4G LTE smartphone</div></div> <br><br><br>-------- Original message --------<br>From: Ralph Castain &lt;rhc@open-mpi.org&gt; <br>Date:  <br>To: Open MPI Users &lt;users@open-mpi.org&gt; <br>Subject: Re: [OMPI users] Open MPI exited on signal 11 (Segmentation fault).	Trying to run a script that uses Open MPI <br> <br><br>Well, it's telling you that your program segfaulted - so I'd start with that, perhaps looking for any core it might have dropped.<div><br><div><div>On Jul 4, 2013, at 8:36 PM, Rick White &lt;<a href="mailto:raw937@gmail.com">raw937@gmail.com</a>&gt; wrote:</div><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"><blockquote type="cite"><div dir="ltr"><div><div><div>Hello, <br><br></div>I have this error:<br>mpiexec noticed that process rank 1 with PID 16087 on node server exited on signal 11 (Segmentation fault)<br><br></div>Wondering how to fix it?<br><br>
